view.name: Data Breach Notifications Affecting Washington Residents (Personal Information Breakdown)
view.attribution: Washington State Attorney General's Office Consumer Protection Division
view.description: - Washington law requires entities impacted by a data breach to notify the Attorney General’s Office (AGO) when more than 500 Washingtonians personal information was compromised as a result of the breach. This dataset breaks out the individual types of breached personal information that were identified in each notice our office received. This data is used to produce the AGO’s Annual Data Breach Report. For additional statistics relating to data breaches, also see the main dataset at: https://data.wa.gov/Consumer-Protection/Data-Breach-Notifications-Affecting-Washington-Res/sb4j-ca4h.

columns.name: DateAware
columns.description: The data the notifying entity became aware that a breach impacting Washington residents had occurred.

columns.name: DateSubmitted
columns.description: The date the notifying entity submitted their notice to the Attorney General’s Office.

columns.name: DataBreachCause
columns.description: The cause of the data breach. Three categories are available. Cyberattack: when a third party deliberately attempts to access secured data, such as information stored on a server, using cyber technology. Unauthorized access: when an unauthorized person purposefully accesses data through means such as an unsecured network or sifting through sensitive documents left out on a desk. Theft or mistake: the mistaken loss of information, such as a clerical error, or the inadvertent theft of information.

columns.name: DateStart
columns.description: The known or estimated start date of the breach.

columns.name: DateEnd
columns.description: The known or estimated end date of the breach.

columns.name: Name
columns.description: The name of the entity providing notice to the Attorney General’s Office. This is nearly always the owner of the breached data, whether or not they were the entity to be breached. E.g. If Company A contracts with Company B to process their data, and Company B is breached, Washington law requires Company A to provide the notice.

top.item: TD Ameritrade, Inc. and Charles Schwab & Co., Inc.

columns.name: CyberattackType
columns.description: This is a sub-category of breaches caused by Cyberattacks. The tracked types include: Malware, Ransomware, Phishing, Skimmers, Other, and Unknown.

columns.name: WashingtoniansAffected
columns.description: The estimated or known number of Washington residents whose information was affected by the data breach.

columns.name: IndustryType
columns.description: The industry type that the notifying entity belongs to. Options include: Business, Education, Finance, Government, Health, and Nonprofit or Charity.

columns.name: BusinessType
columns.description: A sub-category of notifying entities who are categorized as Businesses. Options include: Accessories, Biotech, Cleaning, Clothing, Construction, Consumable, Cosmetic, Cryptocurrency, Entertainment, Fitness, Home, Hospitality, Human Resources, Legal, Manufacturing, Professional Services, Real Estate, Retail, Shipping, Software, Telecommunications, Transportation, and Web Services. There is also an “other” category to capture any businesses that do not fit into the above.

columns.name: InformationType
columns.description: The various types of personal information, as defined by Washington law, impacted in a breach.

columns.name: Year
columns.description: The “year” in which a data breach notice is submitted to the Attorney General’s Office (AGO). As a result of the effective date of the law requiring notice to the AGO, a year starts on July 24 and ends on July 23 of the following year. In other words, a notice submitted on July 23, 2020 would be marked as a “2020” breach, while a notice submitted on July 24, 2020 would be marked as a “2021” breach.

columns.name: WashingtoniansAffectedRange
columns.description: Range of Washingtonians Affected for visualizations

columns.name: BreachLifecycleRange
columns.description: The lifecycle of a breach is the sum of the “Time to Identify”, and “Time to Contain” a breach. This data is measured in days.

columns.name: EntityState
columns.description: The US state of the entity if one was provided
